snippet.textDisplay: People don’t just wake up one day and say “I want to become a heroin addict and shoot up dope.” Or “you know what, I think I will go get an addiction.” Through circumstances, it happens and can happen to ANYONE. You’re naive AF if you think that you’re above an addiction & that it couldn’t ever happen to you. Love, pain, curiosity, boredom, wanting to fit in or get closer to people, wanting to not feel alone, chronic illness, and more can lead you to it. It’s especially easy when you can’t see the warning signs, risks in situations, or when you’re in your own damn way. Over half of the population has some form of an addiction or has precursors to becoming addicted to something. No matter how harmless or harmful an addiction seems, it’s still just that, an addiction. The stigma surrounding addiction needs to stop. It’s not just a certain class, race, age, lifestyle, or person that deals with it. It can be anyone. Your kids, parents, grandparents, siblings, cousins, aunts, uncles, nieces, nephews, best friends, doctors, religious people, students, teachers, neighbours, favourite celebrities, law enforcement, athletes, role models, & world leaders. We can’t rid the world of addiction but we can take steps to be more compassionate, understanding, supportive, open, aware, thoughtful, helpful, respectful, patient, healthy, & kind to one another.
